  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Ishraq in Islam?",
  "response": "In Islam, Ishraq refers to a specific prayer known as Salat al-Ishraq. This is a voluntary prayer that is performed after the sun has risen and has become high in the sky, typically around 15 to 20 minutes after sunrise. The prayer consists of two rak'ahs (units of prayer).\n\nThe term \"Ishraq\" itself means \"to shine\" or \"to radiate,\" which is fitting as the prayer is performed when the sun's light begins to spread and brighten the day. Performing Salat al-Ishraq is believed to bring numerous spiritual benefits and rewards, including the forgiveness of sins and an increase in one's faith and devotion to Allah.\n\nMuslims who perform this prayer often do so as a way to seek additional closeness to Allah and to gain extra spiritual merits beyond the obligatory five daily prayers.",
